label: BODY

label: BODY

text: A.  The Traffic Stop
label: HH1

text: Jones argues it was unlawful for Deputy Klunder to detain him at the scene of the
label: BODY

text: traffic stop after the officer had completed his investigation of the window tint and
label: BODY

text: verified that Jones had a valid driver’s license and registration.  He argues the officer
label: BODY

text: lacked “reasonable or probable cause . . . or any other legal justification” to detain him
label: BODY

text: for the “minor traffic code violations,” and the fact that he did so violated Jones’s
label: BODY

text: constitutional rights.  (Doc. No. 15 at ¶ 3(a))  He further argues the officers’ search of his
label: BODY

text: vehicle incident to his arrest was unlawful because Deputy Klunder’s own report indicates
label: BODY

text: his decision to arrest Jones was based on Jones’s failure to consent to a search of his
label: BODY

text: vehicle.  (Id. at ¶ 3(b))
label: BODY

text: It is well settled that “[a]ny traffic violation, even a minor one, gives an officer
label: BODY

text: probable cause to stop the violator.”  United States v. Lyton, 161 F.3d 1168, 1170 (8th
label: BODY

text: Cir. 1998).  The officer’s belief that Jones’s window tint violated Iowa law constituted
label: BODY

text: probable cause for him to stop Jones and investigate.  Id.  The traffic stop was valid even
label: BODY

text: if it was pretextual and the officer would have ignored the window tint violation absent
label: BODY

text: his suspicion that Jones might be engaged in illegal activities.  United States v. Gomez
label: BODY

text: Serena, 368 F.3d 1037, 1041 (8th Cir. 2004) (citing Whren v. United States, 517 U.S.
label: BODY

text: 806, 813, 116 S. Ct. 1769, 1774, 135 L. Ed. 2d 89 (1996)); United States v. Caldwell,
label: BODY

text: 97 F.3d 1063, 1067 (8th Cir. 1996) (citing United States v. Thomas, 93 F.3d 479, 485
label: BODY

text: The officer then asked questions reasonably related to the stop, including asking
label: BODY

text: for Jones’s driver’s license, vehicle registration, and insurance card.  See Lyton, 161 F.3d
label: BODY

text: at 1170.  When Jones’s behavior caused the officer to become suspicious that Jones might
label: BODY

text: be involved in criminal activity, the officer was entitled to expand the scope of the stop
label: BODY

text: and to detain Jones for a reasonable time to investigate further.  Id. (citing United States
label: BODY

text: v. Ramos, 42 F.3d 1160, 1163 (8th Cir. 1994); United States v. Johnson, 58 F.3d 356,
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: United States v. Beck, 140 F.3d 1129, 1136 (8th Cir. 1998) (Bennett, J., sitting by
label: BODY

text: designation).  In this case, the officer had observed Jones acting in what, in the officer’s
label: BODY

text: experience, was an unusual manner.  Jones had exited his vehicle immediately upon being
label: BODY

text: stopped, and when he was asked for permission to search his vehicle, Jones reached into
label: BODY

text: the back seat and pulled out a few items, stating that was all he had in the vehicle.  Jones
label: BODY

text: had declined the officer’s requests that he look in the glove box for his registration and
label: BODY

text: insurance card.  Jones’s hands were shaking and he appeared nervous.  He became more
label: BODY

text: nervous when he was told the drug dog was coming, and before he exited his vehicle, he
label: BODY

text: rolled up all the windows.
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: an insurance verification.  Despite the fact that the officer was able to verify Jones had
label: BODY

text: a valid driver’s license and the vehicle was registered to him, Jones’s failure to have these
label: BODY

text: items available in the vehicle violated Iowa law.  See Iowa Code § 321.20B (failure to
label: BODY

text: provide proof of financial liability coverage justifies issuance of citation, removal of
label: BODY

text: vehicle’s license plates, and impoundment of vehicle); § 321.32 (registration card must
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: the traffic stop, and provided him with a particularized, objective basis for suspecting
label: BODY

text: wrongdoing, justifying detention of Jones for a reasonable time to investigate further.  See
label: BODY

text: United States v. Yang, 345 F.3d 650, 656 (citing United States v. Linkous, 285 F.3d 716,
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: HH1

text: Jones argues the search warrant application and the magistrate’s accompanying

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: The United States Supreme Court has set the standard for review of a search
label: BODY

text: warrant application, as follows:
label: BODY

text: [W]e have repeatedly said that after-the-fact scrutiny by
label: BODY

text: courts of the sufficiency of an affidavit should not take the
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: probable cause should be paid great deference by reviewing
label: BODY

text: courts.”  Spinelli [v. United States,] 309 U.S. [410,] 419, 89
label: BODY

text: or negative attitude by reviewing courts toward warrants,”
label: BODY

text: [United States v.] Ventresca, 380 U.S. [102,] 108, 85 S. Ct.
label: BODY

text: [741,] 745, [13 L. Ed. 2d 684 (1965)], is inconsistent with the
label: BODY

text: Fourth Amendment’s strong preference for searches
label: BODY

text: conducted pursuant to a warrant [and] “courts should not
label: BODY

text: invalidate . . . warrant[s] by interpreting affidavit[s] in a
label: BODY

text: hypertechnical, rather than a commonsense, manner.”  Id.,
label: BODY

text: . . . .  Reflecting this preference for the warrant
label: BODY

text: process, the traditional standard for review of an issuing
label: BODY

text: magistrate’s probable cause determination has been that so
label: BODY

text: long as the magistrate had a “substantial basis for . . .
label: BODY

text: conclud[ing]” that a search would uncover evidence of
label: BODY

text: wrongdoing, the Fourth Amendment requires no more.  Jones
label: BODY

text: L. Ed. 2d 697 (1960).  See United States v. Harris, 403 U.S.
label: BODY

text: [FN10]  We also have said that “Although in a particular case
label: BODY

text: it may not be easy to determine when an affidavit
label: BODY

text: demonstrates the existence of probable cause, the resolution
label: BODY

text: of doubtful or marginal cases in this area should be largely
label: BODY

text: determined by the preference to be accorded to warrants,”
label: BODY

text: Ventresca, supra, 380 U.S. at 109, 85 S. Ct. at 746.  This
label: BODY

text: reflects both a desire to encourage use of the warrant process
label: BODY

text: by police officers and a recognition that once a warrant has
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: 108, 85 S. Ct. at 745. . . .  [M]any warrants are – quite
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY
